        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Documenting the Scope Statement"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The AIA scope statement is a concise, signed document that defines what is and is not covered before the assessment work begins. It prevents scope creep and provides a clear reference point if the assessment is later challenged:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "yaml"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# aia-scope-CS-HIRING-001.yaml\naia_id: \"AIA-CS-HIRING-001\"\nuse_case_name: \"Resume Screening Assistant\"\nscope_statement: >\n  This AIA covers the automated decision process for initial resume screening\n  of external job applicants for software engineering roles at ExampleCorp.\n  The process begins when a resume is submitted via the applicant tracking\n  system and ends when a hiring manager receives a ranked shortlist.\n  The Claude integration (model: claude-opus-4-8, system prompt: SC-HIRING-001)\n  generates a textual assessment for each candidate; a ranking algorithm\n  then orders candidates by assessment sentiment score.\n\nin_scope:\n  - Resume preprocessing and field extraction\n  - Claude assessment generation\n  - Sentiment scoring of Claude output\n  - Shortlist ranking and presentation to hiring manager\n\nout_of_scope:\n  - Final hiring decision (made by human hiring manager)\n  - Offer negotiation and compensation decisions\n  - Background check process (separate vendor, separate AIA)\n\naffected_population: \"External job applicants for software engineering roles\"\nannual_volume_estimate: 2400   # applicants per year\ntier: \"Tier 2 — Standard AIA\"\nregulatory_triggers:\n  - \"NYC Local Law 144 (bias audit + candidate notice required)\"\n  - \"SOC 2 CC3 (risk assessment for automated decision process)\"\n\nscoped_by: \"compliance@example.com\"\nscoped_date: \"2026-06-01\"\nai_owner: \"talent-platform@example.com\"\napproved_by: \"vp-people@example.com\"\napproved_date: \"2026-06-05\"\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Algorithmic Impact Assessment scoping begins by answering four questions: what kind of decision does the Claude integration inform, who holds decision authority, who is affected, and how reversible are errors? The answers determine whether a Tier 1 lightweight, Tier 2 standard, or Tier 3 full assessment with external review is required — or whether the use case is exempt. A structured scoping interview with weighted scoring makes the tier assignment defensible. The scope statement, signed by the AI owner and an approver before assessment work begins, defines the exact process boundary and prevents both under-inclusion (missing upstream data risks) and over-inclusion (diluting the analysis across an entire product). Regulatory requirements from the EU AI Act, NYC LL144, and Canada's Directive map directly to the three tiers."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
